*1996 National Junior Olympics Gold Medalist at 106&nbsp;lbs.
*1996 World Junior Olympics Gold Medalist at 106&nbsp;lbs.
*1997 National Junior Olympics Bronze Medalist at 112&nbsp;lbs.
*1998 National Amateur Championships Bronze Medalist at 106&nbsp;lbs.
*1999 National Amateur Championships Gold Medalist at 106&nbsp;lbs.
*1999 National Golden Gloves Light Flyweight Gold Medalist
*1999 World Amateur Championships Gold Medalist
*1999 USA Boxer of The Year
*Member of the 2000 US Olympic Team. His results were:
**Defeated [[Sergey Kazakov]] (Russia) 8-6
**Lost to [[Brahim Asloum]] (France) 4-6

==Professional career==
===Flyweight===
Viloria started his professional career as a flyweight and picked up 17 wins with no defeats. He also captured and defended the [[North American Boxing Federation|NABF]] [[Flyweight]] title in the process before moving down to the [[Light Flyweight]] division.

===Light Flyweight===
On September 10, 2005, Viloria dropped down to light flyweight and won the [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] crown by knocking out Eric Ortiz in the first round with a powerful right.

He successfully defended it once on February 18, 2006 against [[José Antonio Aguirre (boxer)]] and was undefeated in 20 bouts. Viloria's unbeaten streak ended when he was dethroned by Mexican [[Omar Niño Romero]] on August 10, 2006.

In a rematch held on November 18, 2006 at [[Las Vegas]], Romero held on to his title with a controversial [[Tie (draw)|majority draw]] decision, with Viloria knocking down Romero twice during the fight. Romero was then stripped of his title after failing a post fight drug test for methamphetamine and the decision was overturned into a no-contest.

On April 14, 2007, he fought [[Edgar Sosa (boxer)|Edgar Sosa]] for the vacant [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] [[Light Flyweight]] title but lost via majority decision.

===Super Flyweight===
Viloria then decided to move up to the super flyweight division and began training under former champion, [[Roberto Garcia Cortez|Roberto Garcia]], at [[La Colonia Youth Boxing Club|La Colonia Gym]] in [[Oxnard, California]].<ref>[http://www.philstar.com/Article.aspx?articleid=444187 Philstar.net - Viloria back to warrior's mentality]</ref>

Brian Viloria won via unanimous decision against Jose Garcia Bernal (26-11-1) in his debut at the [[super flyweight]] division at the Alameda Swap Meet in [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], [[California]] on January 5, 2008.<ref>[http://www.latimes.com/sports/printedition/la-sp-boxing5jan05,1,1910108.story?coll=la-headlines-pe-sports  LATimes.com, Martirosyan scores impressive victory]</ref> Viloria secured four more victories before deciding to move back down to [[Light Flyweight]].<ref>http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2008/Jul/24/sp/hawaii807240379.html</ref>

===Return to Light Flyweight===
On April 19, 2009, Viloria moved back down to junior flyweight to challenge Mexican [[Ulises Solís|Ulises "Archie" Solís]] for the [[International Boxing Federation|IBF]] [[Light Flyweight|Junior Flyweight]] title. Pressured by a fading career due to his past losses in big fights, Viloria defeated Solis, whom at the time of the fight was rated the #1 Jr. Flyweight by [[The Ring (magazine)|The Ring]]<ref>[http://www.ringtv.com/ratings/jr_flyweight/ ringtv.com - Ring Magazine Jr. Flyweight Ratings] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090405055536/http://www.ringtv.com/ratings/jr_flyweight/ |date=April 5, 2009 }}</ref> in the 11th round with a vicious right to the jaw. The official bout stoppage was a KO 2:56 into the 11th round.<ref>[http://www.ringtv.com/blog/576/donaire_and_viloria_score_impressive_kos_in_the_philippines/ ringtv.com - Donaire and Viloria score impressive KOs in the Philippines] {{webarchive |url=https://archive.is/20090422143851/http://www.ringtv.com/blog/576/donaire_and_viloria_score_impressive_kos_in_the_philippines/ |date=April 22, 2009 }}</ref> The fight was held at [[Araneta Coliseum]] in the Philippines, site of the [[Thrilla in Manila]], as the co-main event of the Donaire-Martinez fight. Viloria snapped Solis' 11-fight unbeaten streak, 8 of which were title defenses while extending his win streak to 6.

Viloria successfully defended his [[International Boxing Federation|IBF]] [[Light Flyweight|Junior Flyweight]] title on August 29, 2009 against Jesus Iribe.<ref>http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/171077/sports/boxing/viloria-outboxes-iribe-retains-ibf-crown</ref>

For his second defense, Viloria fought [[Carlos Tamara]] of Colombia on January 23, 2010. Though leading in points, the referee called a halt to the bout in Tamara's favor as Viloria was close to passing out in the twelfth round awarding Tamara a TKO victory and the belt.<ref>http://www.badlefthook.com/2010/1/23/1266149/carlos-tamara-stuns-brian-viloria</ref> Moments following the bout, Viloria passed out due to extreme exhaustion.<ref>http://www.philstar.com:8080/sports/592204/viloria-claims-split-verdict-over-soto</ref>

===Return to Flyweight===
Viloria returned to the flyweight division against Mexico's Omar Soto on July 10, 2010 at the Yñares Sports Arena, Pasig City, Metro Manila.<ref>{{cite web | url =http://www.boxingscene.com/?m=show&id=29136 | title =Brian Viloria Beats Omar Soto By Split Decision Nod | last =Nathanielsz | first =Ronnie | work = | publisher =BoxingScene.com | date =July 10, 2010 | accessdate =July 10, 2010}}</ref>

On July 16, 2011 Viloria captured the [[World Boxing Organization|WBO]] [[Flyweight]] title by besting Mexican [[Julio Cesar Miranda]].<ref>http://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/6777192/brian-viloria-beats-julio-cesar-miranda-win-wbo-flyweight-title</ref> On December 10, 2011 Viloria stopped [[Giovani Segura]] by way of an 8th Round TKO.<ref>http://www.badlefthook.com/2011/12/11/2627812/viloria-vs-segura-results-eighth-round-stoppage-hematoma-swelling-pinoy-boxing-news</ref> On May 13, 2012, Viloria stopped his rival [[Omar Niño Romero]] in the 9th round for another successful defense of his [[World Boxing Organization|WBO]] [[Flyweight]] title.<ref>http://www.badlefthook.com/2012/5/13/3017206/viloria-vs-romero-iii-results-brian-viloria-excorcises-demons-stops-nino-ninth-round-boxing-news</ref>

On November 17, 2012 Viloria challenged [[Hernan Marquez]] in a flyweight unification between his WBO title and the Marquez's WBA crown. He went on to stop Marquez in 10 rounds becoming the first flyweight unified world champion since 1965.<ref>{{cite web
|url=http://philboxing.com/news/story-77247.html|title=BRIAN VILORIA UNIFIES WORLD FLYWEIGHT TITLE AFTER 47 YEARS|date=November 19, 2012|accessdate=2012-11-25|author=Maloney L. Samaco|publisher=PhilBoxing.com}}</ref> Viloria then lost both titles to [[Juan Francisco Estrada]] on April 6, 2013.<ref>http://sports.inquirer.net/94651/viloria-loses-flyweight-belts-to-estrada-via-split-decision</ref>

Viloria picked up four more wins before facing pound for pound king [[Román González (boxer)|Román González]] on October 17, 2015 for the [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] and [[The Ring (magazine)|The Ring]] [[Flyweight]] titles. Viloria was stopped in the 9th round and lost via TKO.

