{{DISPLAYTITLE:List of ''The X Factor'' finalists (UK series 12)}} {{Use British English|date=October 2018}} {{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}} The [[The X Factor (UK series 12)|twelfth UK series]] of ''[[The X Factor (UK)|The X Factor]]'' began on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] on 29 August 2015. The live shows started on 31 October. In a change from previous series, there were seven weeks of live shows instead of the usual ten. Viewers were asked to decide which categories would be assigned to each judge by voting on Twitter during the series premiere.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Daly|first1=Emma|title=X Factor viewers will choose judges' categories for first time ever|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-08-25/x-factor-viewers-will-choose-judges-categories-for-first-time-ever|date=25 August 2015}}</ref> The results were announced on the day the Six Chair Challenge was filmed.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lee|first1=Ben|title=X Factor announces the judges' categories: Who do Simon, Cheryl, Rita and Grimmy have?|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s103/the-x-factor/news/a666373/x-factor-announces-the-judges-categories-who-do-simon-cheryl-rita-and-grimmy-have.html|website=Digital Spy|date=1 September 2015}}</ref> [[Nick Grimshaw]] mentored the Boys, [[Rita Ora]] mentored the Girls, [[Simon Cowell]] mentored the Overs and [[Cheryl Fernandez-Versini]] mentored the Groups.
The twelve chosen finalists were Ché Chesterman, Seann Miley Moore, Mason Noise, Louisa Johnson, Lauren Murray, Kiera Weathers, Bupsi, Anton Stephans, Max Stone, Alien Uncovered, 4th Impact and Reggie n Bollie.<ref name="finalists">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-3289600/Meet-2015-X-Factor-finalists.html|title=Meet the 2015 X Factor finalists: A comeback king, a far out favourite who thinks he'll win and two serious girl power bands make up this year's 12 live show acts|last=Freeth|first=Becky|date=26 October 2015|work=[[Daily Mail]]|publisher=[[DMG Media]]|accessdate=26 October 2015}}</ref> On 29 October, Monica Michael (from the Girls category) was announced as the only wildcard on this series, with all four judges agreeing on it.<ref name="wildcard">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-3295677/Monica-Michael-returns-X-Factor-Wildcard-Rita-Ora-failed-pick-live-shows-emotional-Judges-Houses-audition.html|title='I am back!' Monica Michael returns to the X Factor after Girls mentor Rita Ora reveals she convinced her fellow judges to give the axed singer a Wildcard entry|last=Crawley|first=Joanna|date=29 October 2015|work=[[Daily Mail]]|publisher=[[DMG Media]]|accessdate=1 November 2015}}</ref>
==Boys== The "Boys" category is mentored by Nick Grimshaw. Contestants in this category are male soloists aged between 16 and 25. The six candidates at judges' houses were: Ché Chesterman, Ben Clark, Josh Daniels, Simon Lynch, Seann Miley Moore, and Mason Noise. Grimshaw chose:
===Ché Chesterman=== '''Ché George Chesterman, Jr.''' (born 18 August 1996)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/record?id=bmd%2fb%2f1996%2f9%2f123332401|title=England & Wales births 1837-2006 Transcription for Che George Chesterman, Hackney, 1996|accessdate=8 December 2015|via=[[Find My Past]]|subscription=yes}}</ref> is a singer-songwriter from [[Basildon]], Essex. Prior to auditioning for ''The X Factor'', he used to work stacking shelves at a [[Tesco]] in [[Langdon Hills|Langdon]], Essex, but quit to pursue his singing career.{{Citation needed|date=November 2015}} Chesterman's father, Ché Sr., auditioned for [[The X Factor (UK series 3)|series 3]] of ''The X Factor'' in 2006 and made it through to boot camp.{{Citation needed|date=November 2015}} Chesterman studied music at college, which is where he realised his passion for performing.{{Citation needed|date=November 2015}} He was the lead singer of a band called Jinx, before they split and he decided to audition for the show.{{Citation needed|date=November 2015}}
With the eliminations of Seann Miley Moore in week two and Mason Noise in week four, Chesterman became Grimshaw's last remaining act in the competition. Chesterman was in the bottom two in week four alongside Anton Stephans, but was saved after only Cowell voted to send him home. He was in the bottom two again in week six alongside Lauren Murray and was sent through to the final after the result went to deadlock. He finished in third place in the competition. Chesterman took part in The X Factor Live Tour 2016.
