===Mason Noise=== '''Mason Dominic Binnell''',<ref name="Mason real name">{{cite news|url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/whats-on/film-news/look-x-factor-star-mason-10412793|title=Look at X Factor star Mason Noise before he was famous - and what's his real name?|last=Laws|first=Roz|date=9 November 2015|work=[[Birmingham Mail]]|accessdate=19 November 2015}}</ref><ref name="Mason Noise birth">{{cite web|url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/record?id=bmd%2fb%2f1993%2f8%2f120445595|title=England & Wales births 1837-2006 transcription for Mason Dominic Binnell, Birmingham, 1993|accessdate=19 November 2015|via=[[Find My Past]]|subscription=yes}}</ref> (born 4 August 1993)<ref name="Mason Noise birth" /> known by his stage name '''Mason Noise''', is a part-time McDonald's worker from [[Birmingham]].<ref name="Mason real name" /> Before "The X Factor" he released a few songs and videos that didn't quite make 100 views on YouTube.
Noise was a controversial act because during the six-seat challenge, after performing for his mentor [[Nick Grimshaw|Grimshaw]], Noise complained that his audition was only broadcast for 47 seconds while other contestants were featured for up to 10 minutes. [[Simon Cowell]] responded by saying "You should feel lucky to be on this show. Why don't you shut up?" and called Noise an "arsehole". Noise was booed by the crowd before dropping the microphone and walking off the stage. Noise later told the Daily Mirror: "[Simon] lost control and it was uncalled for. Especially as all I was doing was saying an opinion. I think that no one has ever questioned him before and no one has questioned the format of the show. Something needs to change on that show. Listen to the kids, at the end of the day I have a lot of support on Twitter."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s103/the-x-factor/news/a667013/x-factor-contestant-mason-noise-reacts-to-being-called-an-arsehole-by-simon-cowell-he-lost-control.html|title=X Factor contestant Mason Noise reacts to being called "an arsehole" by Simon Cowell: "He lost control"|last=Harp|first=Justin|date=4 September 2015|work=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=7 September 2015}}</ref> When contestant Tom Bleasby had withdrawn from the show for personal reasons, there was a spare place at judges' houses.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/xfactor/news/tom-bleasby-withdraws-from-the-x-factor|title=Tom Bleasby withdraws from The X Factor|last=ITV|first=ITV|date=12 October 2015|work=ITV|publisher=ITV|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> On 15 October, Grimshaw announced that Noise would replace Bleasby at judges' houses.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s103/the-x-factor/news/a673796/x-factor-nick-grimshaw-confirms-mason-noise-will-replace-tom-bleasby.html|title=X Factor: Nick Grimshaw confirms Mason Noise will replace Tom Bleasby|last=Warner|first=Sam|date=15 October 2015|work=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=27 October 2015}}</ref> There was a negative response about this decision from the media due to Noise's behaviour at the six-chair challenge,{{Citation needed|date=October 2015}} although the remaining five candidates defended Noise, stating that his attitude had significantly improved since the six-chair challenge.{{Citation needed|date=October 2015}}
At judges' houses, Grimshaw put Noise through to the live shows. This decision was met with a mixture of cheers and boos from the audience.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Law|first1=Nina|title=X Factor 2015: the final 12 revealed and five things we learned|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/x-factor/11941456/what-time-is-x-factor-on-tonight.html|accessdate=8 November 2015|work=telegraph|agency=telegraph|publisher=TelegraphEnts|date=25 October 2015|ref=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/x-factor/11941456/what-time-is-x-factor-on-tonight.html}}</ref>
Noise was in the bottom three in week two, having to perform on the sing-off against Seann Miley Moore. Initially, Cowell and Fernandez-Versini voted to send him home because of his sing-off performance. However, Ora claimed that she saw something in him and voted against Moore. Their mentor, Grimshaw, did not want to decide between the two and the result went to deadlock, which guaranteed Noise another week. Noise was eliminated in week 4 after receiving the fewest votes on Saturday. He finished in seventh place. Noise took part in the 2016 X Factor Live Tour.
He has released the singles "Blow the doors off", "Take your seat", "Boyfriend", "Heat", "Loco", "She drives me crazy" and "Stranger" (& My Boyz Beatz)
