===Monica Michael=== '''Monica Michael''' (born 21 October 1989){{Citation needed|date=December 2015}} is a youth worker from [[North London]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/x-factor-contestant-monica-michael-6443774 | title=X Factor contestant Monica Michael insists she won't quit music no matter what happens on the show | publisher=[[Daily Mirror]] | work=mirror.co.uk | date=15 September 2015 | accessdate=15 November 2015}}</ref> and is this series' wildcard contestant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-3295677/Monica-Michael-returns-X-Factor-Wildcard-Rita-Ora-failed-pick-live-shows-emotional-Judges-Houses-audition.html|title=Monica Michael returns to the X Factor|last=Crawley|first=Joanna|date=29 October 2015|work=Mail Online}}</ref> She originally auditioned for [[The X Factor (UK series 11)|series 11]] and got through to bootcamp, but failed to progress past the six-chair challenge after being eliminated by her potential mentor Cheryl Fernandez-Versini. She returned for this series and was eliminated during judges houses by judge Rita Ora but was brought back as a wildcard act as all four judges felt she should have got through.
Michael was in the bottom three in week three. She performed in the sing-off against Anton Stephans, receiving Cowell's and Grimshaw's votes to eliminate her. The result went to deadlock and she was sent home as the act with the fewest votes. Michael finished in seventh place, missing out on a place in The X Factor Live Tour 2016. Since leaving the show, Michael has released "Pretty Little Sister" and "My Angel" which she sang at her 2014 audition and judges houses in 2015. In 2018, she released her third single "Wish you love", followed by the songs "Diamond in the rough", "Soldier" and "Long gone".
