===Anton Stephans=== '''Anton Stephans''' (born '''Stephen Johnson''')<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailystar.co.uk/tv/x-factor/473356/X-Factor-Anton-Stephans-pretending-to-be-adopted|title=X Factor hopeful Anton Stephans is reportedly not adopted|last=Okey|first=Regan|date=2 November 2015|work=[[Daily Star (British newspaper)|Daily Star]]|accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> is a former backing vocalist from Suffolk and has worked with Tina Turner, Elton John and Sting. He also once performed with [[Sinitta]] in a West End musical.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-11-07/everything-you-need-to-know-about-x-factors-anton-stephans|title=X Factor 2015 acts: Anton Stephans - first audition to Judges' Houses videos|last=Daly|first=Emma|date=7 November 2015|work=[[Radio Times]]|accessdate=24 November 2015}}</ref>
With the eliminations of Bupsi in week 1 and Max Stone on week three, Stephans became Cowell's last remaining act in the competition. He was in the bottom three on week three and had to perform in the sing-off against Monica Michael, receiving Ora's and Fernandez-Versini's votes to be eliminated. The result was deadlocked and he was spared since he had the most votes. The following week, he was in the bottom two alongside Ché Chesterman and was eliminated by the judges, receiving only Cowell's vote to save him and becoming the last of his acts to leave the competition. He finished in sixth place. He took part in The X Factor Live Tour 2016.
